{# Schema notes (post-2026-05-08, after 4732f7e Dockerfile rewrite for new upstream):

   The new upstream Puter (v2.5.x dist build at /opt/puter/config.default.json)
   moved `database` and `s3` from `services.{database,file-cache}` to the
   top level of config. The clients are instantiated via
   `new ClientClass(this.#config)` (server.js:84) and read straight from
   `this.config.database` / `this.config.s3` (no `services` unwrapping).
   A nested override under `services.database` is silently ignored by
   deep-merge — the runtime then falls through to the default
   `database.path = "volatile/runtime/puter-database.sqlite"`, which
   resolves under the read-only WORKDIR `/opt/puter` for the runtime
   user `node` (uid 1000) and crashes with
   `TypeError: Cannot open database because the directory does not exist`
   at better-sqlite3/lib/database.js:65.

   `file-cache` is removed from the schema entirely (no consumer in
   /opt/puter/dist/src/backend) — keeping the old key was harmless but
   pointless.

   Absolute `/var/puter/...` is the bind-mounted data dir from the host
   ({{ puter_data_dir | default(ansible_facts['env']['HOME'] + '/puter') }}/data),
   pre-created with mode 0755 in roles/pazny.puter/tasks/main.yml and owned by
   `node:node` inside the container. Aligns with the absolute paths already
   used by roles/pazny.puter/tasks/{post,apps}.yml (was a latent split-DB
   bug pre-rewrite). #}
